problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-k-sorted-lists/description/
Approach: Min Heap (Priority Queue)
Intuition

Each linked list is already sorted, so the smallest element among all lists must always be one of the current heads of the linked lists.

Instead of comparing all nodes repeatedly, we use a min heap to keep track of the smallest available node from each list.

Whenever we remove the smallest node:

Add it to the result linked list.
Move to the next node in that same linked list.
Add that next node to the heap.

This ensures that we always choose the smallest available node.

Algorithm
Create a dummy node to build the resulting linked list.
Maintain a pointer prev which represents the last node in the merged list.
Initialize a min heap:
Insert the head node of every non-empty linked list.
Store (node value, list index, node):
node value decides the priority.
list index acts as a tie breaker when two nodes have the same value, because Python cannot compare ListNode objects directly.
While the heap is not empty:
Remove the smallest node from the heap.
Attach it to the result list.
Move prev forward.
If the removed node has a next node, insert that next node into the heap.
Return dummy.next, which is the head of the merged linked list.

Complexity
Let:

k = number of linked lists
N = total number of nodes across all lists
Time Complexity:

Each node is inserted into and removed from the heap exactly once.

Each heap operation costs:

O(logk)

Therefore:

O(Nlogk)
​

Space Complexity:

The heap contains at most one node from each linked list:

O(k)
​

The dummy node and pointers require constant extra space.

Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
import heapq
class Solution:
    def mergeKLists(self, lists: List[Optional[ListNode]]) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        dummy = ListNode(0)
        prev = dummy
        heap = []
        n = len(lists)
        for i in range(n):
            if lists[i]:
                heapq.heappush(heap,(lists[i].val,i,lists[i]))
        while heap:
            val , index, node = heapq.heappop(heap)
            prev.next = node
            prev = prev.next
            if node.next:
                heapq.heappush(heap,(node.next.val,index,node.next))
        return dummy.next
